<h2>Choosing the Right Varieties</h2>
<p>
        In short growing seasons, focus on:
      </p>
<ul>
<li>Early or short-season varieties (55–70 days)</li>
<li>Determinate types for quicker production</li>
<li>Smaller fruit types (cherry, saladette) for reliability</li>
</ul>
<p>
        Large beefsteak varieties often require longer seasons and warmer nights to fully mature.
      </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Common Short-Season Mistakes</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Starting too late indoors.</strong> This shortens harvest time.</li>
<li><strong>Transplanting too early.</strong> Cold soil delays growth significantly.</li>
<li><strong>Ignoring fall frost planning.</strong> Fruit needs time to ripen before first frost.</li>
</ul>
<p>
        To plan your fall cutoff date, use the
        <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost &amp; Fall Planting Planner</a>.
      </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Can Tomatoes Finish in Your Season?</h2>
<p>
        Count backward from your first frost date using your variety’s days to maturity.
        If your remaining warm days are tight, consider:
      </p>
<ul>
<li>Using row covers in early fall</li>
<li>Pruning excess growth mid-season</li>
<li>Removing late flowers 4–6 weeks before frost</li>
</ul>
<p>
        Reliable maturity depends on both calendar days and temperature consistency.
      </p>
</section>

